For those who donât know me, my name is Cong Minh and Iâm 100% Vietnamese. I was born in Hanoi and have moved to Poland at 2 years old. Me and my family travelled a lot, so I may have some experience to share.

Poland has a really extensive history record reaching back to year 900. Due to geographical and political reasons, it hasnât really been an attractive place to visit. Well, still isnât but itâs becoming more and more. How? Few reasons.

First and foremost is wide use of social media. Back in the day, people heard about outside world from either radio or tv broadcast and obviously being technologically limited and governments having control, people didnât know much about any country to be fair. 

But social media are just a convenience. As mentioned earlier, Poland has a very long history. Combined with ease of information access, it became a must for history nerds. Many events such as recreation of Battle of Grunwald, visiting Westerplatte, the old town, countless museums, they all add up to being one of the best places to learn about any world war. 

But growth wouldnât be possible without things to do in between those highlights. In the past, finding a place to stay was a bit more challenging that it is today. My family used to roam around the city looking for guesthouses to stay. Now itâs just browsing booking com, looking for a hotel and calling it a day.

Unfortunately with high demand comesâ¦ high cost. Basically everything from hotels to food has become more and more expensive and itâs not only affecting tourists. Local community also tries to stay afloat in this crazy highly connected world.

Itâs not all bad though. Having foreigners pump money into the economy and forcing better infrastructure is sure going to benefit everyone staying here.

Thank you for coming to my Ted Talk. Iâm Cong Minh and I hope to see you next time. Goodnight!
